Music Genre Classification

Based on Song Sentiment

Aleksandra Gawor, Paulina KuÅ‚akowska

1. Introduction

1.1. Research questions

In this paper we aim to utilize text mining, NLP and sentimental analysis to mine for patterns in associating the sentiments within a song with its genre. Is it possible to associate the mood of a song with the genre? Are some words more popular for a certain genre and appear more frequently? Is it possible to predict the genre basing only on the sentiment of a song and its lyrics?

1.2. Literature overview

2. Methodology

2.1. Data set

For the sake of analysis, we used Kaggleâ€™s dataset 380,000+ lyrics from MetroLyrics. The initial data consisted of 339277 observations of 6 variables. Our dataset is a sample of 20000 rows.

2.2. Text preprocessing

The first step was to draw a sample from our data and remove subspaces that were included in our data set.

### draw data sample 
data.sample <- data[sample(nrow(data), 20000),]

lyrics <- subset(data.sample, data.sample != "")
## Warning: Length of logical index must be 1 or 20000, not 120000

Then, we did a tokenization, which breaks the text into individual tokens and transforms it into a data structure, in our case, unnested into a wordâ€“i.e.Â extracting words from lyrics.

lyrics <- lyrics %>% unnest_tokens(word, lyrics)

After tokenization it was time to remove all weird characters from the newly created â€œwordâ€ column.
Because some songs included special or foreign language characters there was a need to get rid of them. Also, we needed to exclude some typical for lyrics phrases, like â€œchorusâ€, â€œverseâ€ etc.

## Joining, by = "word"

Our songs in the dataset included also stop words not only from English but also from other foreign language songs. There was, therefore, a need to remove Spanish and French stop words as well.

custom_stop_words1 <- bind_rows(stop_words,

                                          lexicon = "custom"))
custom_stop_words2 <- bind_rows(stop_words,
                               data_frame(word = quanteda::stopwords("french"),

lyrics <- lyrics %>%

## Joining, by = "word"
lyrics <- lyrics %>% 
  mutate(word = iconv(word, from = "latin1", to = "ASCII")) %>%
  filter(!is.na(word))

The most negative sentiments we can find in the Hip-Hop music, while the genre of Pop has much more words associated with rather good emotions. Sentiments most prevalent in Hip-Hop music are the ones of anger, fear and disgust. Also, many vulgar, profanity words come mostly from Hip-Hop lyrics and are also included in the top negative words from our â€œContribution to Sentimentâ€ graph and wordclouds. The Hip-Hop genre as well as Pop may be groups that would be easy to classify by the sentiment (polarity) predictor.

3. Classification

3.1. Extracting polarity

# Positive / negative ratios and polarity 

lyrics_bing <- lyrics %>%
  inner_join(get_sentiments("bing"))
## Joining, by = "word"
lyrics_polarity <- lyrics_bing %>%
  count(sentiment, song) %>%
  spread(sentiment, n, fill = 0) %>%
  mutate(polarity = positive - negative,
         percent_positive = positive / (positive + negative) * 100,
         percent_negative = negative / (positive + negative) * 100)

# we only need 'genre' variable as well
lyrics_genre <- lyrics %>% select(c("song", "genre"))

# drop duplicates (we are interested in whole song, not observations for each word)
lyrics_song <- unique(lyrics_genre)

# now we are ready to combine the two sets of variables
lyrics_set <- merge(lyrics_song, lyrics_polarity, by = "song")

# we set the genre to factor, to read it as a response variable
lyrics_set$genre <- as.factor(lyrics_set$genre)

3.2. Genre polarity and sentiment visualization

# Genre polarity visualization 
lyrics_set %>%
  ggplot( aes(genre, polarity, fill = genre)) +
  geom_col() +
  scale_fill_manual(values = colors) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0, color = "red") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 11)) +
  xlab(NULL) + ylab(NULL) +
  ggtitle("Polarity by Genre")

3.2. Support Vector Machine

set.seed(123456)
training_obs <- createDataPartition(lyrics_set$genre, 
                                    p = 0.7, 
                                    list = FALSE) 
lyrics.train <- lyrics_set[training_obs,]
lyrics.test  <- lyrics_set[-training_obs,]

# Defining the model formula and training the model
svm.model <- svm(genre ~ negative + positive + polarity + percent_positive + percent_negative, 
                 data = lyrics.train)

summary(svm.model)

lyrics_set$prop <- within(lyrics_set, genre[genre == 'Country'] <- 'Country')
prop <- lyrics_set$prop

# Proportion visualization

ggplot(prop, aes(x = genre, fill = genre))+ 
  theme_bw()+
  geom_bar()+
  labs(x = "Genre", y = "Song count", title = "Song Count by Genre")

3.3. Results and conclusions

The sentimental analysis of words provided us some interesting relationships when it comes to genre of a song and its lyricsâ€™ sentiments. We were able to observe some most frequent words within distinct music genres, and genresâ€™prevailing sentiments. Unfortnately, however, we were not able to make prediction that would classify the genre of a song correctly, basing of a songâ€™s polarity. Yet, our model worked simillarly to the ones from other researchers. What could be done to improve the model is for example downsampling to balance the data or try using only the most common genres, when also applying some tuning. What is more, there could be very low variability of our data whent it comes to polarity, and most genres are simply too similar or neutral. The easiest to predict should be for example Hip-Hop (most negative genre), or Pop which is rather positive.
